The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, with a combined 29 percent
The appreciable weakening of the two parties of the previous grand coalition and the significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties were brought about by the early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday, according to the first preliminary results.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly strong losses, with the position of the current president, Wilhelm Molterer, shaking gravely.
Conversely, the election leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthian Governor Jörg Haider is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the country's Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest party in the country, with 29.8 percent of the vote, but it loses 5.5 percent of the vote against the latest 2006 election.
Worse still, the ÖVP, which loses almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of both of these major parties in Austria's post-war history and, especially for the Peoples, who triggered the early elections, a literally disastrous result.
As recently as the beginning of July, when the ÖVP withdrew from the coalition, the People's Party had a significant lead in their preferences over the SPÖ.
But voters apparently punished them for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, speculation about the possible resignation of the party chairman and incumbent vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers reckons that this could happen as early as Monday at a special meeting of the party's bureau.
Such a development would probably facilitate the path to the still most likely starting point from the election result, the renewal of the grand coalition of the SPÖ and the ÖVP.
However, given the strengthening of the two right-right populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ), they received a preliminary 18 percent of the vote and the BZÖ eleven per cent of the vote - the Social Democrats also voiced concerns about the replay of the years in 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (then the FPÖ was still united, and the BZÖ split from the BZÖ) in the joint government, which even raised sanctions from the European Union.
Haider is clearly betting on this development, having already said he was ready to work with any party and anticipate a return to Vienna for national politics.
The Green Party was still in the parliament, but it lost easily and fell among the Austrian political parties from third to fifth.
Neither of the other parties apparently surpassed the 4% threshold and made it to parliament.
