The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Yet we are missing something here - a virtual operator that would make the classic ones cheaper.
He may not miss long.
We have written about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe at all, on Mobil.cz.
Indeed, this was confirmed by ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
Following the European Commission's latest steps in the field of regulating roaming charges, this may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are holding so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to get into a fight.
It may sound paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and penetrating to over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to be glad to say that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, the chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, often chipper, who has commented several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network does not seem to have much chance (after all, it would be hard to find frequencies anymore).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
The entry of virtual operators into the mobile market brought about a significant price reduction, to which even classical operators then had to respond.
At the same time, before the entry of the pike like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices in the UK as in the UK.
But it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we don't have to go too far for examples.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, the operator has managed to recruit more than 100,000 customers and become the country's fifth largest operator.
At the same time, the financial group Penta, which owns U:fona in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
Indeed, they need far fewer customers to function effectively than a classic operator.
They do not entail the relatively high cost of the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators tend to profile themselves as low-cost - offering cheap calls and SMS, but this is often counterbalanced by a shortfare service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as much cheaper as its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobile being Mobile was in Poland, the bet on the novel target audience can also be a pretty good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"Carcise guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if a similar concept could be caught up in our country.
Vodafone's press spokesperson Miroslav Čepický doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings."
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look too hopeful.
Rather, the Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studničková, press spokesperson for the Penta financial group, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
It has thus confirmed toil that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are certainly not in favour of this idea.
Rather the opposite, they are trying to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been fabled for a long time by GTS Novera, which would like to take the next step to become a real competitor to Telefónica O2 in the corporate customer field.
"We have a great interest in offering not only fixed but mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already managed to move forward in the negotiations," says the group's press spokesperson, Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe there's a look on better days.
From the unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should be looking forward to perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room for the creation of a fully-fledged virtual operator on the Czech market.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far, no subject has approached us with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2 said in his comments to Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also invoked by other operators.
T-Mobil's press spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with O2's comments: "We have not yet recorded any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which it would be possible to further build."
He adds: "It is difficult for a virtual operator to appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we'd have to have a specific agreement on the table to think about this short term."
Vodafone is more likely to focus its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický says: "By negotiations with potential virtual operators, we are open, especially in the area of burden and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial in terms of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, leading to a fall in prices and thus a decline in their profits.
So why make the take-up easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when operators are at a point, they can pull together, is also evidenced by the tussle over the formation of the U:fona.
Perhaps the most pressure towards ČTÚ came at the time of the creation of U:fona from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the ČTÚ website.
But now it is U:fon who is useful as an argument for not letting the virtual operator in.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive mobile market environment was recently exacerbated by the entry of a fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another player would make high demands on him and, above all, his services."
However, given this approach by mobile operators, the sheer disinterest of the Czech regulators is a heating disinterest.
This is not just about the attitude of ČTÚ, which unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in competition in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries.
These are exclusively owned by the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took his typical stance on the whole issue.
"A virtual operator's access to the mobile market would be possible after a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator to lease the necessary infrastructure were concluded.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential bidders was probably not interesting enough for the classical operators," Kristián Chalupa of the External Relations Department of the Office said in response to our inquiry.
The comments thus formulated will not be surprised by the representatives of the operators.
From an office to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one is to use their market position, it is more than a poem.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators normally operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephone services."
But apparently the pressure to function properly in the market environment and the decline in prices are not among the interests of the OBR.
In fact, the shocking thing about the case is the touching tingling of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is entirely self-eminite.
Like the exact same price of petrol at petrol stations, it is surely just a coincidence and a tough competition.
"The Office did not find signs of anti-competitive conduct on this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore has no adequate increased responsibility for its market conduct.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual operators are most likely missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in his comments.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets carried out by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is the only market in terms of competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer a different perspective - the consent of the network operator is always needed to create a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically, has a monopoly on its network.
So in a segment, it necessarily has to be dominant.
But even if we did not allow this argument, it should be minimally cautionary tale for the OBR that the three mobile operators are doing strikingly similarly.
At the same time, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera) show that they face very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
The uproar of the responsibility at ČTÚ is then a rather common trick in telecommunications, with which the OHS hands off the matter.
We've met him in a few similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of ČTÚ's powers to the field of competition in telecommunications failed to enforce, although a number of experts promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the OHS must know this more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It's all the while no one's looking
At the same time, the functioning of some pseudo-ovturtour operators, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own price lists of mobile telephony services, but they are only partially public.
They are usually companies engaged in multilevel marketing.
The likes of Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price statements of these firms usually reach only the elect.
The charm lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic corporate customer to the operator, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a major customer, they will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators forbale forbumbor such.
"If there were cases of which you are referring to, it could be a violation of the contractual terms that we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question on the problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such activity would not be brought to accountable people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is opending to do so.
They make significant profits from the activities of these firms, and yet - unlike the actual virtual operators - they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, however, the services of these companies are used by only a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card on their phone is not in their name, so they cannot dispose of it fully as regular customers of mobile operators."
But that is what should be at least strange to ČTÚ.
In addition, another question is being raised for the OBR.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the OBR has relatively strong powers to expose such activity, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be content with the operators' explanation that they have no idea about this and their terms of trade prohibit it.
When we will not be the most expensive
As the text has already been mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought about a noticeable drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, classical operators sought to hinder their creation more or less.
The arguments used by them were virtually identical - too small, or perhaps too saturated, service quality problems, etc.
But it was in the developed countries that the regulators intervened at these moments, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but of their customers.
Whether by formal measures or informal pressure, they then achieved the fact that the first virtual operator was created and others packed on it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are tossing the case around like a hot potato.
We cannot escape the impression from our experience that ambiguity in competencies is more than suited to them in these cases.
But let's not throw a gun in the toil.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator will really appear in our country soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the operators admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the OBR to remain inert for refusing (discrimination) to other candidates.
And we might stop calling for more than in the rest of Europe.
