Honda hits for the second time with its bestseller
In the month of November, Honda will launch a second-generation Jazz.
If the predecessor of this single-space vehicle already had considerable space, it now offers an even more spacious interior.
This is joined by improved engines that increase the comfort of the ride and allow for greater fuel savings.
Evolution rather than revolution.
Such is the second generation Honda Jazz.
Although aesthetically, the lines of the new Jazza are very similar to the previous model, there have been many changes to this single-seat car.
It should be mentioned, for example, in innovative design, a new platform, larger dimensions and new engines.
Before we explore the new model, it should be noted that the new Jazz comes on the market six years after the launch of the first generation.
That's why the first thing we notice is that Honda needed a shorter period to rejuveni this model than other manufacturers.
Although the Jazz is a lesser-known model in Europe, it has become a phenomenon in other markets.
This is the case for Japan, the country where the Jazz was the best-selling car in 2002, as well as during this year's 2008 year.
It has been in Japan that nearly a million units have been sold since the launch of the Honda Jazz.
The second market became the old continent, with approximately half a million units sold in six years.
Honda, however, aims to boost sales in its category for the new Jazz.
Thus, while in 2007 the Japanese company sold a total of 83,000 Honda Jazz units, in 2009 estimates are projected to be 100,000 cars, which would mean an increase of 17% in the European market.
As far as the Spanish market is concerned, Honda has sold a total of 8,000 Jazz units since 2002, representing 6.7% of Honda's total sales in Spain.
As for the new generation of Jazz, the Spanish branch's management expects to sell 2,000 units for the whole year.
It is the arrival of the new Jazza that will make it possible for Honda to significantly ease the decline in sales in Spain.
The company's management thus de facto expects the year to be concluded with a total of 22,000 units sold, which is 4,000 fewer than in 2007 and a 16% drop.
Despite this increase in sales, Honda increased its share of the Spanish market to 1.8%, compared to 1.6% from last year.
In 2010, the Japanese firm expects to reach 2%.
To achieve this share, Honda is relying on the success of its next new model.
It is the Honda Insight, a five-door compact-size hybrid with a length of 4.37 metres, from which the Japanese company promises to sell around 200,000 a year worldwide.
As far as markets are concerned, the Japanese manufacturer estimates that 50% of Insight will be sold in the United States, while the remaining percentages will be shared between the old continent and Japan.
The launch of Honda Insight is expected to launch in the first months of next year as it is presented to the public in Valencia in January.
Compared to the first generation, the new Jazz has increased all dimensions.
Its length increased to 3.9 metres (by five centimetres more), a width of 1.69 metres (two centimetres more) and a wheelbase to 2.5 metres, which means an extension of five centimetres.
The height, on the other hand, has not changed and is still 1.52 metres.
The larger dimensions were also enlarged by the interior space.
This advantage was achieved both by using a new platform and by stowing a fuel tank in the middle of the car, which had already been used at the previous Honda Jazz.
Also, the luggage capacity - which has a double bottom system - increased to 399 litres, 19 litres more than the volume of the first-generation luggage compartment.
It should be noted that these dimensions occur with the 1.4 engine version, as the luggage capacity at the Honda Jazz 1.2 is 379 litres.
Another improvement, in addition to external features - such as rear LED lights or the possibility of equipment with a glass panoramic roof - is easier to access the rear seats.
The doors leading to the second row of seats allow an angle of opening of 80 degrees, compared to the first Jazz.
For the second-generation Honda Jazz, the engines are new.
At the outset, this small model will be offered with two 1.2 and 1.4-litre petrol engines.
Both engines use i-VTEC technology that allows lower consumption, lower carbon dioxide emissions and provides excellent improvements to the propulsion system at the same time as high torque in full engine speed.
The first 1.2-litre engine has a power output of 90 horsepower at 6,000 rpm with a maximum torque of 114 Nm at 4,900 rpm.
This engine - which had a 2.3-litre consumption of the previous generation of the Jazz 78 horsepower - has a consumption of 5.3 litres and a 125 grams of CO2 emissions.
Compared to the previous engine, which reached 83 horsepower for the previous generation, the current one will reach 100.
The 100-horsepower Honda Jazz 1.4 has a combined consumption of 5.4 litres and an emission of 128 grams of CO2.
