"Auto bee" prevents precipitation
To advance the development of anti-mon-air accident technologies, Nissan was this time inspired in nature, specifically with bees.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes to model the flying of bees, thus preventing collisions.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in precipitation prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Center for Technical Advances Nissan Motor Co. developed the robot in collaboration with the Centre for Progress in the scientific and technology research of the prestigious Japanese University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhir Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology, R&D of the Brand, BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan's four zones of Nissan's security shield.
The robot is tasked with strengthening the ability to prevent precipitation in cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
The most important, however, are the folded bee's eyes, which are able to be seen in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, which makes it possible to fly in its personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual feature, the engineers designed what they called the Laser Range Finder.
It records obstacles that are located up to two metres within a 180-degree radius of the BR23C, calculate the distance of the object and sends out the signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
"The moment the obstacle is recorded, the robot mimics the beehive movements and immediately changes the direction by turning the wheels into the right or even larger angle to prevent the collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is that all evasive maneuvers are perfectly instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and Chief Engineer of the project.
The robot, unlike bees, cannot move upwards and downwards or diagonally, its movement is limited to two dimensions and the direction that is made possible by rotating its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and capabilities as for bees.
Nissan therefore used the rotation function in addition to acceleration and slowing down to prevent the robot from colliding.
"The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and act according to this data.
It does not require the preservation of information or logical intuitions from previous manoeuvres, which allows it to function without interruption with only two dozen kB of memory.
This may come as a surprise to you, but with memory, we don't talk about the gig or the mega."
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for immediate precipitation prevention, a technology for which Nissan predicts to be used in serial cars in a decade.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion.
Another possible future use of this technology could be to build the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would take the driver to its destination, avoiding obstacles on the road.
Drivers repeatedly caught with alcohol in their blood will have to install "alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior is demanding that a driver with three administrative penalties for drunk driving must have to install a system in his car to prevent him from getting the car started drunk or if he is not in a breath.
The proposal became known in June of this year and is now included in the annual report of the Supreme Prosecutor's Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will take one year.
Its aim is to return the driver behind the wheel, so drivers will also have to complete a course for the commute re-education.
In addition to the National Transportation Safety Authority, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Technological Institute for the Safety of Automobile Safety (FITSA) will also participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75% of the car drivers accused more than once to be behind the wheel in this state, are behind the wheel again.
Alcolock should prevent this as it is a system connected to a vehicle that measures the alcohol level in the exhaled air and prevents the car from being started if the driver is not innoid before or if it is recorded above the permitted concentration of alcohol.
Its price exceeds EUR 1 000 and the culprit himself would have to pay for it.
A study conducted in this sense in the US in 2007 showed that for vehicles equipped with this equipment, offences had decreased by 65 % during the first year of the introduction.
Spain is expected to save the lives of 115 people every year.
The measure is limited to administrative penalties for two reasons: for this behaviour to be dealt with before it is a criminal offence.
And to help its implementation, as the legislation can be implemented in the usual way, but the necessary legislation of the criminal provisions requires an amendment to the law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any sales version, although it has already been installed in some industrial and public service vehicles.
Just tomorrow, Congress of Deputies will vote on the PSOE (Spanish Workers' Socialist Party) proposal, recommending to install this system on school buses, as is the case in France.
