Héma-Québec celebrated his tenth anniversary yesterday, and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly rejoicing, as Héma-Québec became one of the world's most reliable and efficient blood suppliers.
Above all, it has regained the public's trust, which was seriously shaken after the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is widely known, the state-owned blood reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross transfusion Department was contaminated with the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and a wave of public reign, the Canadian Government launched a public investigation in February 1994, presided over by Judge Horace Krever, which was intended to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to formulate a recommendation that such a disaster should not be repeated.
While Judge Krever delayed handing over the report, some of the provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélinea Committee stood up for this role.
After the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were set up in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to be farmed by Quebec, and the Canadian bloodstream to supply all provinces and both territories.
"When Héma-Québec began his activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system," recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was disheartening.
By sustained efforts to increase the safety of blood products and constant work in this area over the coming years, we have regained public confidence," he says, adding, proudly that in early 2008 Héma-Québeku, nearly 94% of the québean population had already trusted.
Dr. Décary, however, does not lose sight of "trust is something very fragile."
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the principle of prudence.
"At that time, we have seen many cases of human form of mad cow disease occurring in Europe, a new variant of a disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease," says the woman who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea whether this disease could spread through the blood.
We were therefore based on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report, according to which, when we do not know and when the spread of a serious illness is at stake, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterised by the degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, the precaution must be taken.
In April 1999, we therefore rejected blood from people who have been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that the disease was transmitted through the blood.
This episode has shown us that it made sense to adhere to the precaution principle."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting the HIV virus appeared on the market: tests with the use of nucleic acid (NAT) that allow the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the donor blood, and not the presence of the antibodies on which the tests were based were used before.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the patient's infection and the moment when the first viruses can be detected by our blood techniques, the specialist explains.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have, in essence, reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without even knowing it and without us being able to figure out.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of obtaining AIDS through a blood transfusion.
The risk of getting blood from contaminated with HIV is now exposed to one person in 12 million.
"In other words, this means that by the time someone gets infected with HIV, you will need to distribute 12 million blood products.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission occurs via a blood product.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe the blood transfusion necessary for recovery in absolute peace," says the head of Héma-Québek's management.
"The challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what a disease-causing element may appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by the stab of insects.
It is necessary to be cautious at all times," continues Dr. Décaryová, stressing that in addition to the safety supply, Héma-Québec must also factor in the supply sufficient.
"The needs are growing because the population is aging.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelet.
