Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, while in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed as the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only 7,000 of them are treated. The cause of this is that the sufferers often do not know they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the aggregate naming of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, with liver and jaundice inflammation, but the agents of the disease and the diseases they cause differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruss are spreading in two main causes, depending on the disease,: hepatitis A and E digestive system (for example, in-infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses of blood and bodily fluids (sperm, ash, saliva).
In any case, travelers should be protected by vaccination against A and B, the vaccine does not exist against the C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after taking the infected meal, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdomination, urges to vomit.
Then, jaundice, a lightened stool is formed on the skin and the whale of the eye and the whale of the eye, and darkening the urine. The treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people die worldwide from a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that an estimated one in ten of the infected is treated with medication.
hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most of the infected are not even aware of their illness, the disease's agents are destroying liver cells insidiously, and so the first symptoms come in many cases in 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention, regular depotage, is very important.
In three groups, the disease occurs a lot more often than on average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, between drug users, and a tattoo among people.
Currently, the projected global number of individuals infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
As the disease can already be demonstrated by a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact their general practitioner if they record any sign of unknown origin.
When detected early, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body to prevent contagion and prevent cancer from occurring.
September 30 is the world day of hepatitis, which was organised by the organisations representing the sick for the first time in 2004.
It aims to draw attention to chronic liver inflammation caused by these viruses, the causes of its origin and the importance of early detection of the disease.
