Intelligent car imitates bumblebee flight
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collision, if not imitations, of obstacle detectors occurring in the world of nature?
For example, bees.
The initial strategic idea of the surprise project, presented at the CEATEC trade fair in Japan, was given to Nissan's engineers by bumblebees. It was about how to build a new generation of systems that prevent collision.
In collaboration with the Tokyo University, Nissan designed a biomimetic robotic management system of the BR323C type, a robotized minicar that is equipped with bee properties, with the ultimate aim of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective packaging," explained Kazuhiro Doi, CEO of the brand for technology PR and R&D, at the exhibition.
Composite eyes play an important role, allowing bees to bee in all directions at the field of view of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eye, the engineers reached for the idea of a laser range.
This identifies the obstacles up to 2 metres in front of the BR23C in the field of view of 180 degrees, calculate their distance and sends the on-board microprocessor a signal that immediately transforms into a collision-movie operation.
The obstacle is caught in a split second, then begins to imitate the bee's movements and turn the wheels to the extent needed to prevent the collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this folding maneuver takes place in an absolutely instinctive way.
"If that were not the case, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," explains Toishyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the Robotic Car Project.
It must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology suits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety protective cover within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The process must be reflected in what the bee is doing to avoid other bees.
This process must not take longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed up, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless options offered to the bees when avoiding, only the possibility of rotating movement, acceleration and slowing were applied to the robotic car.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer service life than the lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, the important is the instinctive, intelligent response, not the ability to process, much less data storage.
This mechanism must only be processed and responded to a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need for him to store and respond using an intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres, so he is constantly using only a memory of a few kilobytes.
It does not need memorabilia with giga- or megaabyte capacity.
This is the first step to develop instant evasive technology, which Nissan estimates could reach for the mass-produced cars in a decade.
Another possibility of application may be a link to the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles, would lead the motorist to the specified final destination.
